{META_DATA}: T H E G R E E N M I L E
{META_DATA}: Screenplay by Frank Darabont
{META_DATA}: from the novel by Stephen King
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: First Draft
{META_DATA}: 11/4/97
{META_DATA}: "We each owe a death, there are no exceptions..."
{META_DATA}: A SONG BEGINS, distant as a faded memory on an old Victrola:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once I built a railroad, made it run... Made it race against time...Once I built a railroad, now it's done...Brother, can you spare a dime...
{META_DATA}: Opening credit sequence
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: plays against footage of the Great Depression, images haunting and sepia-toned, defining an era.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bread lines...the soup kitchens...the dust bowl refugees heading west with their possessions on their backs and no hope in their eyes...the strutting gangster royalty flaunting their bootleg riches...an entire generation of lost youth riding the rials...the U.S. army troops raining truncheon blows on the half-starved and forgotten veterans of World War One as "Hooverville" is set afire in the very shadow of the nation's capitol...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All these faces, all these lives, in a world not really so very long ago...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD - DAY(SLOW MOTION)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...where cattails sway in the sepia-toned heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A small scrap of fabric is snagged in the nettles, fluttering languidly...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COLOR BLEEDS SLOWLY IN as mosquitoes swarm and dragonflies skitter, showing the fabric scrap to be pale yellow...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, a MAN WITH A SHOTGUN comes crashing through the cattails, wiping through frame and exiting...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...then ANOTHER MAN...and ANOTHER...armed with rifles, plowing through the brush, exiting frame...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and now comes KLAUS DETTERICK, a farmer one step above shirt-tail poor, a double-barrel shotgun in the crook of his arm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pauses, horrified, seeing the scrap of cloth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls it loose, turns back, screaming something in anguish...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and still more men come crashing into view, flooding by us with dreamlike, slow-motion grace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ONE MAN is leading a team of DOGS, trying to untangle the leads.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DEPUTY ROB McGEE is shouting for everybody to stay together...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and under it all, we hear a sibilant, frightening whisper:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WHISPERING VOICE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: You love your sister?
{DIALOGUE}: You make any noise, know what happens?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And off that horrible voice, we
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GEORGIA PINES NURSING HOME - MORNING(PRESENT DAY)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CLOCK RADIO spews the morning weather report, abruptly pulling us into the present with a prediction of rain.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL EDGECOMB, late 70's/early 80's, wakes to another day...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PAUL'S ROOM - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul stands at his bathroom mirror, meticulously buttoning his shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He picks up a hairbrush, starts tidying his hair...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CORRIDOR - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE OLD AND INFIRM haunt these corridors like ghosts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A WOMAN inches along on a walker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A MAN shuffles by with a rolling I.V. stand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The floor is a limey, institutional green.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul comes into view, spry for his age, murmurs an occasional greeting.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BREAKFAST ROOM - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DOZENS OF RETIREES are having breakfast, sipping weak coffee or tea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some chat and gossip, other are content to keep their own company, some just stare slackly into space.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul enters, sees ELAINE CONNELLY sitting with a few other ladies, sipping tea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's 80, refined and elegant, his best friend here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She gives him a good-morning smile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives her a rakish wink in return, which makes her smiles all the more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul reaches past the people at the counter and sneaks two pieces of cold leftover toast off a serving plate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tosses Elaine another look--catch ya later--and exits.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HALLWAY PAST KITCHEN - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul slips to the back door unnoticed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Identical red plastic rain ponchos line the wall on pegs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He helps himself to one and eases outside, making good his escape.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NURSING HOME - ESTABLISHING - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nestled in a valley of wooded hills, a drizzly mist rolling over the treetops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul appears f.g., coming up the ridge in his borrowed poncho.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks back at the valley below, inhales deeply-- this is a man who loves his walks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls a piece of toast from his pocket and starts to nibble as he presses up on the ridge...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Low angle: nursing home and ridge beyond
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and we see Paul from a distance, just a speck trudging up toward the treeline.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A PICKUP TRUCK rumbles into frame and parks, a bumper sticker looming large: "I Have Seen God and His Name Is Newt Gingrich".
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BRAD DOLAN gets out, an orderly in his late 20's/early 30's, arriving for work in jeans and cheesy plaid shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gazes up toward the ridge, scowling and muttering softly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Old fuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He slams the door and heads for the nursing home...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WOODS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as CAMERA BOOMS DOWN through the trees to find Paul wandering a wooded path, munching a tidbit of toast, looking for all the world like Red Riding Hood in his plastic poncho.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's silent here, like a church.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The only sounds we hear are the twittering of the birds and the hammering of the woodpecker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A RUSTLING SOUND makes Paul freeze.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns, becomes transfixed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Softly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, my...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reverse angle
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: reveals a magnificent BUCK, not twenty feet away, misty breath punching the cold morning air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They watch each other for an endless moment, both standing stock still...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and then the animal bounds away, vanishing into the foliage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul lets out a breath, shakes his head in wonder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes another bite of toast, moves on...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and WE PAN WITH HIM to reveal a pair of old wooden storage shacks along the path up ahead.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SHACK - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dark in here, cobwebby and decrepit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Paul approaching outside the grimy window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He steps up to the glass and shades his eyes, peering curiously in as we
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NURSING HOME - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul approaches the back door, returning from his walk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches for the knob...and a figure in white lunges from behind the dumpster to grab his wrist.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He whirls, gasping in fright--it's Brad Dolan, wearing his orderly's uniform.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Out for a little stroll, Paulie?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Let go...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul tries to pull away, but Dolan's got him tight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: What's with this poncho you got on, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't yours.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I got it off the wall there.
{DIALOGUE}: There's a whole row of them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: But not for you, Paulie, that's the thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Those are for the staff.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I just borrowed it.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't see what harm it does.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: It's not about harm, it's about rules.
{DIALOGUE}: You probably don't think an old fart like you has to mind rules anymore, but that's just not true.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad's eyes keep shifting--he obviously doesn't mind abusing the elderly as long as he doesn't get caught doing it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry if I broke the rules.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: You got no business up in those woods anyway, especially in the rain.
{DIALOGUE}: What if you fall and bust a hip, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Who you think's gonna have to hoss your sorry old bacon back down here?
{DIALOGUE}: Me, that's who.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You're hurting me!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: What do you do up there, anyway?
{DIALOGUE}: You're too old to go jerk off, so what do you do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: I just walk, that's all, I like to walk!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad lashes out and grabs Paul's other hand, which he's been holding tightly clenched shut.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Come on.
{DIALOGUE}: Open up.
{DIALOGUE}: Let Poppa see.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul uncurls his fingers, revealing the crushed remnants of a bit of toast, his palm slick with a greasy oleo smear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They turn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine stands just inside the screen door with a cup of tea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad's eyes become calculated, wondering how much she's seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine keeps her tone level, betraying nothing:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I saw you coming back, thought you'd like some tea.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Are you coming in?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Dolan and I were...chatting.
{DIALOGUE}: About the weather.
{DIALOGUE}: I think we're through now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad lets Paul loose, leans close:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Paulie?
{DIALOGUE}: You tell anyone I squeezed your po' ol' hand, I'll tell 'em you're having senile delusions.
{DIALOGUE}: Who you think they'll believe?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad walks off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul turns, watches him go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The screen door opens and Elaine steps out, her face pale.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul gives her a strained, though grateful, smile as we
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TV ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jerry Springer's on the tube, whipping his studio audience into a frenzy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAN OFF TO REVEAL DOZENS OF OLD FOLKS watching on couches and folding chairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old black fellow named PETE is grousing to a GROUP OF ELDERLY LADIES...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Why we always watch this crap?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELDERLY LADY #1
{DIALOGUE}: It's interesting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PETE
{DIALOGUE}: Interesting?
{DIALOGUE}: Bunch'a inbred trailer trash, all they ever talk about is fucking...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and WE CONTINUE PANNING to Paul and Elaine sitting near the back, talking quietly as Paul rubs his bruised hand:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: We should report him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: That might just provoke him all the more, make things worse for everybody.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: It's not everybody he has it in for, Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: It's you.
{META_DATA}: (off his look)
{DIALOGUE}: What did you do to provoke him in the first place?
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: He's just an abusive bully, and should be made to stop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Ellie, please...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pete
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is at the TV, switching channels while:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELDERLY LADIES
{DIALOGUE}: ...no, the Movie Classic channel is further down...past the Home Shopping...keep going...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finds the Movie Classic channel, which is playing an old black and white musical--"Top Hat," with Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A delighted reaction:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELDERLY LADY #2
{DIALOGUE}: Oh!
{DIALOGUE}: This is wonderful...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: idly shifts his gaze to the TV...and his expression goes slack with recognition and dismay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine sees the look in his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He glances away...even briefly considers walking out...but in the end, he can't help himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The past just caught up with him with a freight-train wallop, and, for one, he decides to ride the rails...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks back at the TV.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On screen, Fred and Ginger have begun their famous "Cheek to Cheek" number, with Astaire singing in that sublime, easy-go-lucky way of his:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FRED ASTAIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Heaven, I'm in heaven...and my heart beat so that I can hardly speak...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLOW PUSH IN on Paul, watching.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He'd like to take his eyes off the screen, but the movie has him in a grip tighter than Brad Dolan's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine is watching him with puzzled concern:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No response.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All he can hear is that music, all he can see are those dancers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The figures on TV are gliding with ghostlike grace in their silvery, phosphor-dot world of long ago...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul abruptly bursts into tears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room goes quiet, everything comes to a standstill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All eyes turn, some concerned, others merely curious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul just sits sobbing into his hands, shoulders heaving.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Paul...my God...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ORDERLY
{META_DATA}: (rushing over)
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{DIALOGUE}: What's wrong?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: It's okay...I'll be okay...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another orderly appears--Brad Dolan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He puts his hand on Paul's shoulder and leans close, feigning concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: S'matter, Paulie?
{DIALOGUE}: Why the boo-hoo- hoo?
{DIALOGUE}: Something nasty happen?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine shoves his hand away, eyes flashing with anger.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Edgecomb will be perfectly fine without your help, thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad back off with a "hey, suit yourself" gesture.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine helps Paul to his feet and leads him out.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SUN ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul is staring out the windows, pensive and drained.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's raining now, pattering the glass and the lawn beyond.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine waits across from him, wishing he would speak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Softly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I guess sometimes the past just catches up with you, whether you want it to or not.
{DIALOGUE}: It's silly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Was it the film?
{META_DATA}: (off his look)
{DIALOGUE}: It was, wasn't it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't spoken of these things in a long time, Ellie.
{DIALOGUE}: Over sixty years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She reaches out, gently takes his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm your friend.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Yes you are.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul wonders if he's even up to talking about it after all this time...and decides that perhaps he is:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I ever tell you I was a prison guard during the depression?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: You've mentioned it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Did I mention I was in charge of death row?
{DIALOGUE}: That I supervised all the executions?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This does come as a surprise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She shakes her head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: They usually call death row the Last Mile, but we called ours the Green Mile, because the floor was the color of faded limes.
{DIALOGUE}: We had the electric chair then.
{DIALOGUE}: Old Sparky, we called it.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I've lived a lot of years, Ellie, but 1935 takes the prize.
{DIALOGUE}: That was the year I had the worst urinary infection of my life.
{DIALOGUE}: That was also the year of John Coffey, and the two dead girls...
{META_DATA}: FADE TO BLACK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In blackness, a title card appears:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "The Two Dead Girls"
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GEORGIA COUNTRYSIDE - DAY (1935)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HUNDREDS OF PRISONERS work the fields, pickaxes rising and falling in waves, a prison song being sung in cadence with the work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GUARDS patrol on horseback, rifles aimed at the sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A late 20's Ford PRISON TRUCK comes chugging into view along the road, kicking up a long trail of dust in the heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It seems to be riding unusually low on its rear suspension.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COLD MOUNTAIN PENITENTIARY - ESTABLISHING - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Depression-era prison in the south.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The prison truck sways down the rutted dirt road toward the main gate...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK TOILET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...while Paul Edgecomb, early 40's, stands in a cramped toilet in his guard's uniform, trying to piss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His face is pained, his forehead beaded with sweat.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK (THE GREEN MILE) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BRUTUS HOWELL(nicknamed "Brutal" for his intimidating size, but he's actually rather thoughtful by nature) stands at the entry door of the cellblock, peering out through a viewing slot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sees the prison truck arrive at the main gate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and nods to fellow guard DEAN STANTON sitting at the duty desk, then cross the Green Mile--a wide corridor of faded green linoleum running some sixty paces top to bottom, with four large cells to a side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal steps to the bathroom, listen a moment, knocks softly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: Prisoner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Christ.
{DIALOGUE}: Gimme a minute.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal waits patiently, a bit embarrassed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finally hears a THIN TRICKLE, accompanied by a stifled groan of pain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: You all right in there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: For a man pissing razor blades.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens, revealing Paul's pale and sweaty face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: You should'a took the day off, gone to see the doctor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: With a new arrival?
{DIALOGUE}: You know better.
{DIALOGUE}: Besides, it's not as bad as it was.
{DIALOGUE}: I think it's clearing up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They hear the truck HONKING as it rumbles up outside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul gives them a nod to resume their positions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul walks down the Mile, passing the cells where two inmates reside--the first is ARLEN BITTERBUCK, a Washita Cherokee; the second is EDUARD DELACROIX("DEL"), a skinny Cajun.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEL
{DIALOGUE}: New boy coming in, boss?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Never you mind, Del, you just keep your nose quietly on your business.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul arrives at the end of the Mile, takes up a position at an empty cell.
{META_DATA}: (Down at this end, past the cells, is E Block's version of the "hole" -- a padded room where violent inmates are sent to cool off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It isn't used very often...in fact, at the moment, it's doubling as storage space.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: peers out the viewing slot as the truck stops outside.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Damn, they're riding on the axle.
{DIALOGUE}: What'd they do, bust the springs?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GUARDS PERCY WETMORE AND HARRY TERWILLIGER OF E BLOCK emerge from the back of the truck and step down, turn back...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tighter angle on back of truck
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We get our first glimpse of the new inmate as a pair of GIGANTIC BLACK FEET step down into the yard...and the rear of the truck bounces back up on its springs where it belongs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: sees what's coming, eyes widening slightly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: You might wanna reconsider getting in the cell with this guy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Why's that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: He's enormous.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Can't be bigger than you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal tosses him a look--just wait.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swings the door open in a hot flood of daylight, giving us our first good look at:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John coffey
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is a huge black man, nearly 7 feet tall and 300 pounds, his massive head shiny and bald, his skin a tapestry of old scars, his prison overalls (the biggest size they had) ending at mid-calf.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks dull and confused, as if wondering where he is and how he got there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy and Harry lead him toward E Block in shackles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy's got his hickory baton out of it custom-made holster, hollering:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: Dead man walking!
{DIALOGUE}: Dead man walking here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside the cellblock
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul can't see them approach from where he stands, but he can certainly hear Percy:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Jeezus, pleeze-us, what the hell's he yelling about?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Up by the door, Brutal just rolls his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy is the first one through the door, still hollering...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: Dead man walking!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...then Coffey enters, ducking low to get through, his shadow blotting out Brutal and Dean as his massive frame fills the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everything hangs suspended for a moment, a look of "hold shit" written on everybody's faces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy keeps yanking on the big man's cuffs, leading him along with a cry of:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: Dead man walking!
{DIALOGUE}: Dead man--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Percy, that's enough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy falls reproachfully silent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul doesn't dignify it, just motions for them to come on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The procession comes down the Mile, with Brutal and Dean bringing up rear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: You sure you wanna be in there with him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{META_DATA}: (looks to Coffey)
{DIALOGUE}: Am I gonna have trouble with you, big boy?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey shakes his head slowly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul takes the clipboard transfer papers from Harry, turns and enters the cell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey just stands outside the cell and waits, as if he doesn't understand the concept.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul motions him to come on in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey starts to comply, but Percy raps him smartly with the tip of his hickory baton to get him moving faster.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey flinches, enters the cell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul stares angrily at Percy, who stands slapping his hickory baton against the palm of his hand like a man with a toy he's itching to use.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Percy.
{DIALOGUE}: They're moving house over in the infirmary.
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you go see if they could use some help?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: They got all the men they need.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you just go make sure?
{META_DATA}: (off his look)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't care where you go, Percy, as long as it's not here at this very moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy flushes red, the baton hovering near his palm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks like he's about to say something, but thinks better of it and stalks angrily up the Mile instead...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and sees Del at his bars, smiling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Infuriated, Percy swings his baton and smashes Del's fingers with a LOUD CRACK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Del jerks back, howling in pain:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEL
{DIALOGUE}: OWW, GOD, HE BUS' MY FINGERS!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: Wiped that grin off your shitpoke face, didn't I
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Goddamn it, Percy!
{DIALOGUE}: Get the hell off my block!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy throws Paul a look of disdain--your block, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swaggers out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Del's on his knees, weeping from the pain:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEL
{DIALOGUE}: Oww, damn, boss, he done bus' my fingers for true...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: We'll get it looked at, Del, now keep yourself quiet like I said!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Del falls silent, moaning over his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul turns to Coffey, who looks unsettled by all the commotion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: If I let Harry take those chains off you, you gonna be nice?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry enters to remove Coffey's shackles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Your name is John Coffey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{META_DATA}: (deep and quiet)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir, boss, like the drink, only not spelt the same.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: So you can spell, can you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey shakes his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry steps out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: My name is Paul Edgecomb.
{DIALOGUE}: If I'm not here, you can ask for Mr. Terwilliger, Mr. Howell, or Mr. Stanton...those gentlemen there.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't like the rest of the prison.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a quiet place, we like to keep it that way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey considers this carefully, puzzled.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: It weren't me making all the noise, boss.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{META_DATA}: (eyes narrowing)
{DIALOGUE}: You having a joke on me, John Coffey?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul sees he isn't joking, continues:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Your time here can be easy or hard, depends on you.
{DIALOGUE}: If you behave, you get to walk in the exercise yard every day.
{DIALOGUE}: We might even play some music on the radio from time to time.
{DIALOGUE}: Questions?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey doesn't miss a beat, as if he's been waiting to ask:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Do you leave a light on after bedtime?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul blinks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the last thing he expected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey smiles uneasily, as if they might think him foolish for asking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Because I get a little scared in the dark sometimes.
{DIALOGUE}: If it's a strange place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul looks to his men.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The guards are trading glances.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: It's pretty bright in here all night long.
{DIALOGUE}: We keep half the lights burning in the corridor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Cor'der.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey looks confused.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul points to the lights lining the ceiling of the Green Mile in wire mesh cages.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Right out there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey nods, relieved.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then he surprises everybody by offering Paul his hand, as if to show proper manners.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul hesitates, oddly touched, then surprised his men even more by accepting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey's hand swallows his.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey shakes gently, lets go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul steps from the cell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal slides the door shut, locks it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey stands a moment as if unsure what to do, then sinks onto the cot with his hands clasped between his knees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks up at Paul, his voice soft as a whisper:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Couldn't help it, boss.
{DIALOGUE}: I tried to take it back, but it was too late.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul turns, leads his men up the Mile...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL'S INNER OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and they enter a few moments later.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul is furious, but keeping a lid on his temper:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Dean, run Delacroix up to the infirmary and see if his fingers are broken.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Course they're broken, I heard the damn bones crack.
{DIALOGUE}: Goddamn Percy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: You hear what he was yelling when we brought the big dummy in?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: How could I miss it, Harry?
{DIALOGUE}: The whole prison heard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This makes Brutal snort, breaking the tension--the others can't help smiling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: You'll probably have to answer for sending him off the Mile.
{DIALOGUE}: He's gonna cause you trouble over this, you mark me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I'll chew that food when I have to.
{DIALOGUE}: Right now I wanna hear about the new inmate...aside from how big he is, okay?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{META_DATA}: (smiles)
{DIALOGUE}: Monstrous big.
{DIALOGUE}: Damn.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Seems meek enough.
{DIALOGUE}: Looks like they sent us an imbecile to execute.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Imbecile or not, he deserves to fry for what he done.
{DIALOGUE}: Here...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry tosses a pair of manila envelopes bound with rubber bands on the desk before Paul--Coffey's file.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: ...make your blood curdle.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. E BLOCK PRISON YARD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A small are reserved for inmates of the Mile, fenced-off from the main prison yard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Arlen Bitterbuck walks the perimeter under the watchful eyes of guard BILL DODGE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We find Paul sitting by himself on the bleachers with Coffey's file on his knees, thoughtfully unwrapping his brown- bagged sandwich.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PUSH SLOWLY IN as he begins to read...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. DETTERICK FARM - DAWN (FLASHBACK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and we see Klaus Detterick walk from his house to the barn with a milking pail, a solitary figure against a brightening horizon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He disappears into the barn...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and we hold for a long moment, the house silent b.g.,chickens clucking and scratching in the front yard...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...until a WOMAN'S SCREAM shatters the silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Klaus reappears, dropping the pail, running toward the house...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL ON BLEACHERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as Paul turns the page, keeps reading...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DETTERICK HOUSE - DAWN (FLASHBACK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and Klaus bursts in to find his wife MARJORIE absolutely frantic with terror:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KLAUS
{DIALOGUE}: WHAT?
{DIALOGUE}: GOD SAKES, WHAT?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: THE GIRLS!
{DIALOGUE}: THE GIRLS ARE GONE!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She drags him through the house to a screened-off porch area where their 12 year old son HOWIE is pointing and shouting--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HOWIE
{DIALOGUE}: Papa!
{DIALOGUE}: Papa, look!
{DIALOGUE}: The blood!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: --and Klaus freezes there, stunned to see blood spattered on the floor and the screen door hanging off its hinges...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KLAUS
{DIALOGUE}: Oh my God.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL ON BLEACHERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as Paul absently takes another bite of his sandwich, not really tasting it, keeps reading...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DETTERICK HOUSE - DAWN (FLASHBACK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...plunging us back into the screaming chaos: Klaus grabbing up shotgun shells, Howie loading the .22 rifle he got for Christmas, Marjorie sobbing incoherently...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KLAUS
{DIALOGUE}: GODDAMN IT, WOMAN, GET ON THE PHONE NOW!
{DIALOGUE}: YOU TELL 'EM WE HEADED WEST!
{DIALOGUE}: MIND WHAT I'M SAYING!
{DIALOGUE}: WEST, Y'HEAR?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and she goes stumbling through the house, grabbing for the phone as her men disappear toward the porch b.g.:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: Central!
{DIALOGUE}: Central, are you on the line?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, God, please, somebody took my little girls...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OUTSIDE THE HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Klaus and his son race from the house, following spatters of blood across the yard...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL ON THE BLEACHERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as Paul lets out a long breath, turns the page...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COUNTRY ROAD/FIELD - DAY (FLASHBACK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ---and we see CARS AND TRUCKS pulling up, MEN jumping out with rifles, pouring down the incline toward the field where Klaus is hollering and waving his arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Deputy McGee comes sliding down from the road, taking charge at the top of his lungs--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: McGEE
{DIALOGUE}: I WANT ALL THE WEAPONS UNLOADED, Y'HEAR?
{DIALOGUE}: TAKE OUT YOUR SHELLS, I WON'T HAVE A MAN SHOT BY ACCIDENT TODAY!
{DIALOGUE}: BOBO, WHERE THEM DOGS?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: --and the dogs come bounding out of the back of a truck, howling down the incline to lead the chase...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS ANGLES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...which takes us through the cattails and bulrushes...to the spot where Klaus finds the little scrap of pale yellow fabric, turns and screams...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KLAUS
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Lord, this belongs to my Katie...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and they keep going, stopping abruptly as they find: A blood-drenched area of tramped grass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little girl's bloody nightgown hangs in the low branches of a tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some of these strong men look like they might throw up or faint at the sight of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their blood freezes in their veins as an INHUMAN HOWLING commences up ahead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's like nothing they've ever heard before, raising the hackles of men and dogs alike.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL ON BLEACHERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as Paul quietly turns another page, shaking his head...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD - DAY (FLASHBACK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men reload their weapons.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everybody's terrified.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: McGee starts off, the other following his lead toward--
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE RIVER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: --where they emerge from the treeline, drawing ever closer to the source of that INHUMAN HOWLING...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and they stop, gazing in horror:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John Coffey sits on the riverbank in bloody overalls, his huge feet splayed out before him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's making that inhuman howling sound, face twisted in monstrous grief, pausing occasionally to take in a great hitching breath of air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Curled in his massive arms are the naked bodies of Detterick's 9 year-old twin girls, their once-blonde hair now matted to their heads with blood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tableau.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men staring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John Coffey howling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A train puffing smoke across the landscape.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Klaus Detterick breaks the moment, lunging down the riverbank in a headlong rush.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The others try to grab him, but he shrugs them off and throws himself on Coffey with a scream of inarticulate rage, kicking and punching, fists flying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey barely seems to notice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The others catch up with Klaus, drag him off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He falls to his knees on the riverbank, sobbing into his hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Howie runs to him, throws himself into his father's arm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They hug each other tightly, overwhelmed with grief.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A semblance of quiet descends, except for Coffey's heartbroken wailing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A ring of rifle toting men forms around him, though he hardly seems aware of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: McGee steps forward, uncertain:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: McGEE
{DIALOGUE}: Mister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey goes quiet at once, eyes still streaming tears.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: McGEE
{DIALOGUE}: Mister?
{DIALOGUE}: Can you hear me?
{META_DATA}: (Coffey nods)
{DIALOGUE}: You have a name?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: John Coffey.
{DIALOGUE}: Like the drink, only not spelt the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: McGee hunkers carefully down, watching for any sudden moves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: McGEE
{DIALOGUE}: What happened here, John Coffey?
{DIALOGUE}: You want to tell me that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I couldn't help it.
{DIALOGUE}: I tried to take it back, but it was too late.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: McGEE
{META_DATA}: (pause)
{DIALOGUE}: Boy, you are under arrest for murder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: McGee spits in Coffey's face...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL ON BLEACHERS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as Paul looks up with a slight start, jarred from his reading to find WARDEN HAL MOORES standing before him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: I interrupt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just about done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul stows the file as Hal settles onto the bleachers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: How's that pretty gal of yours?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: Melinda's not so well, Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: Not so well at all.
{DIALOGUE}: Got laid up with another headache yesterday.
{DIALOGUE}: Worst one yet.
{DIALOGUE}: She's also developed this weakness in her right hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Doctor still think it's migraines?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hal gives a slight shake of his head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be taking her up to Indianola next day or so for some tests.
{DIALOGUE}: Had X-rays and the like.
{DIALOGUE}: She is scared to death.
{DIALOGUE}: Truth to tell, so am I.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: If it's something they can see with an X-ray, maybe it's something they can fix.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls a letter, hands it to Paul.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: This just came in.
{DIALOGUE}: D.O.E. on Bitterbuck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul glances toward Bitterbuck, scans the letter, nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't come all the way down here just to hand me a D.O.E.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I had an angry call from the state capital about twenty minutes ago.
{DIALOGUE}: Is it true you ordered Percy Wetmore off the block.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: It is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sure you had reason, but like it or not, the wife of the governor of this state has only one nephew, and his name happens to be Percy Wetmore.
{DIALOGUE}: I need to tell you how this lays out?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Little Percy called his aunt and squealed like a schoolroom sissy.
{META_DATA}: (Hal nods)
{DIALOGUE}: He also mention he assaulted a prisoner this morning out of sheer petulance?
{DIALOGUE}: Broke three fingers on Eduard Delacroix's left hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't hear that part.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sure she didn't either.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: The man is mean, careless, and stupid.
{DIALOGUE}: Bad combination in a place like this.
{DIALOGUE}: Sooner or later, he's gonna get somebody hurt.
{DIALOGUE}: Or worse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: You and Brutus Howell will make sure that doesn't happen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Easy enough to say.
{DIALOGUE}: We can't watch him every minute, Hal.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: Stick with it.
{DIALOGUE}: May not be much longer.
{DIALOGUE}: I have it on good authority that Percy has an application in at Briar Ridge.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: The mental hospital?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{META_DATA}: (nods)
{DIALOGUE}: Administration job.
{DIALOGUE}: Better pay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Then why's he still here?
{DIALOGUE}: He could get that application pushed through...hell, with his connections, he could have any state job he wants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hal has no answer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul look off toward Bitterbuck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Tell you what I think.
{DIALOGUE}: I think he just wants to see one cook up close.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hal follows Paul's gaze, takes his meaning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: Well, he'll get his chance then, won't he?
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe then he'll be satisfied and move on.
{DIALOGUE}: In the meantime, you'll keep the peace.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Of course.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAL
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, Paul.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hal rises, slapping yard dust off his trousers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You give Melinda my love, okay?
{DIALOGUE}: I bet that X-ray turns out to be nothing at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hal walks off looking like he's got the weight of the world on his shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul looks at the letter again...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIGHT ON LETTER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...which is head: Date Of Execution."
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PAUL'S HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul is at the kitchen table in the wee hours of the morning, drinking buttermilk and listening to SOFT MUSIC on the radio.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JANICE EDGECOMB appears, shuffling sleepily downstairs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, you.
{DIALOGUE}: Music too loud?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: There's just this big empty spot in the bed where my husband usually sleeps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: He said to tell you he's having a little trouble with that tonight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She comes into the kitchen, strokes his hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's an easy familiarity and a deep love between these two.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Worried about Melinda and Hal?
{DIALOGUE}: Is that what's got you up?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that.
{DIALOGUE}: Things.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Things.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sits on his lap and gives him a crooked smile--you're not getting off that easily.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Got a new inmate today.
{DIALOGUE}: Big, simple-minded fella.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Do I want to hear what he did?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: One sleepless member of this family's enough.
{META_DATA}: (softly)
{DIALOGUE}: The things that happen in this world.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a wonder God allows it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She gives him a tiny kiss above his left eyebrow, in that special spot that makes him prickle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Why don't you come to bed?
{DIALOGUE}: I've got something to help you sleep, and you can have all you want.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Don't I wish.
{DIALOGUE}: I've still got something wrong with my waterworks, I don't want to pass it on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: You see Doc Sadler yet?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: No, because he'll want me to take sulfa tablets and I'll spend the rest of the week puking in every corner of my office.
{DIALOGUE}: It'll run its course all by itself, thank you very much for your concern.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She kisses that spot above his eyebrow again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He smiles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Poor old guy...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN TIGHT ANGLES: Copper plugs are cleaned, switches are oiled, circuits are tested...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EXECUTION CHAMBER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as maintenance is performed on Old Sparky by JACK VAN HAY and a small crew.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul is carefully sanding a connector plug.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dean is waxing Old Sparky's wooden arms to a gleam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Dean pause, thinking they hear a LAUGH drifting in from E Block...and then Brutal calls softly to them:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: Dean?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Dean enter to find Brutal trying not to wake the cons in their cells by laughing too loudly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They follows his gaze down the Mile, see nothing, turn to him like he's crazy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: I guess the legislature loosened those purse-strings enough to hire on a new guard.
{META_DATA}: (off their looks)
{DIALOGUE}: Look again.
{DIALOGUE}: He's right there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Dean look again and this time they see it:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tiny brown mouse is coming up the Mile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It trots a short distance, peers right and left as if checking the snoring inmates in their cells, then makes another forward spurt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: He's doing a cell check.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This gets them all trying not to laugh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse draws ever closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dean starts to look worried.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: It ain't normal for a mouse to come up on people that way.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe it's rabid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, my Christ.
{DIALOGUE}: The big mouse expert.
{DIALOGUE}: The Mouse Man.
{DIALOGUE}: You see it foaming at the mouth, Mouse Man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{META_DATA}: (dubious)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't see its mouth at all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That does it--Paul and Brutal burst out laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse stops before them and peers up, curling its tail primly around its paws as if to wait.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The guards fall silent, fascinated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bitterbuck stirs in his cell, sits up to watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal tears off a piece of his half-eaten corned beef sandwich, holds it delicately out with two fingers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse rises up, appraising the morsel with shiny black eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: Aw, Brutal, no!
{DIALOGUE}: We'll be hip-deep in mice around here...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{META_DATA}: (to Paul)
{DIALOGUE}: I just wanna see what he'll do.
{DIALOGUE}: In the interests of science, like.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul shrugs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal drops the scrap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse grabs it and eats, sitting up like a dog doing a trick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse turns and scurries back down the Mile, vanishing under the restraint room door at the far end.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dean throws Paul an "I told you so" look.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: He's in the damn restraint room.
{DIALOGUE}: You know he's gonna be chewing the padding out of walls and making himself a nice little nest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal give Paul a sheepish look--well?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul sighs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: All right.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's get the damn mouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stride grimly down the Mile to the restraint room door, men on a mission.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey's awake now, peering from his cot.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Saw me a mouse go by.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: It was a dream.
{DIALOGUE}: Go back to sleep.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Weren't no dream.
{DIALOGUE}: It was a mouse all right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Can't put anything over on you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul unlocks the door, revealing a padded room filled with storage: cleaning supplies, buckets of paint, mops and ladders, you name it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal shrugs off his jacket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul grabs a mop from a steel bucket, hands it to Dean.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Dean, watch the door.
{DIALOGUE}: He tries to get past you, whack him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: Brutal or the mouse?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Har har, Mouse Man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal and Paul start doing the heavy lifting, muscling an unused filing cabinet out the door...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and they finally relay the last few heavy buckets of paint onto the Mile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Brutal catch their breath, scanning the empty restraint room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their eyes go glaringly to Dean.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You let him get past you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: No I didn't, I was here all the time!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Then where the hell is he?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They move slowly into the room, peering into every nook and cranny, utterly mystified.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal shakes his head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Three grown men.
{DIALOGUE}: Outsmarted by a mouse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEAN
{DIALOGUE}: Well, bright side is, all this commotion probably scared him off for good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that's right.
{DIALOGUE}: That's the last we'll see of him...
{META_DATA}: FADE TO BLACK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN BLACKNESS, A TITLE CARD APPEARS:
{META_DATA}: "The Mouse on the Mile"
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A low, static shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Green floor stretching before us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry and Bill Dodge are at the desk b.g., doing paperwork and filing chores.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy is idling nearby, whistling softly and combing his hair...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and into this quiet shot, deep in foreground, creeps the mouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts walking the Mile as before...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...right toward Percy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COFFEY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: stares through his bars as the mouse goes by...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PERCY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: keeps combing his hair, unaware...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DEL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: sits quietly picking his nose in his cell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse appears outside the bars, cruising inexorably up the Mile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Del turns slowly, watches the mouse go by...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PERCY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: still grooming himself, still unaware...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE MOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: keeps coming closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE UP to Bitterbuck peering through his bars, watching him go by...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PERCY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: keeps working that comb--and freezes at the sound of a TINY SQUEAK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His head swivels slowly...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and there's the mouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Staring at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That moment of eye contact reveals an enmity older than time itself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: If mice have a natural enemy, Percy is it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You little son of a bitch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry and Bill glance up from their work.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'll be damned.
{DIALOGUE}: There he is, big as Billy-be-frigged.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought Brutal was pulling my leg.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILL
{DIALOGUE}: That's a goddamn mouse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Brute said he was in here last night begging for food, came right up to the desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILL
{DIALOGUE}: My ass.
{DIALOGUE}: Give him some room, Percy, see what he does.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy takes a few careful steps back, eyes never leaving the mouse.
{META_DATA}: (Percy's hand starts easing toward the handle of his baton.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse comes up to the desk as before.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Brave little bastard, gotta give him that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry breaks off a small piece of cracker and drops it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse picks it up, starts to eat.
{META_DATA}: (Percy's hand inches ever closer to his baton)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILL
{DIALOGUE}: Here, lemme try.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bill drops a piece of cracker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse ignores it completely, keeping its beady little eyes on Harry.
{META_DATA}: (Percy's hand starts easing his baton from its holster.)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILL
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe he's full.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{META_DATA}: (grins)
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe he knows you're just a floater.
{DIALOGUE}: Gotta be an E Block regular to feed the E Block mouse, don'cha know...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry drops another piece--and sure enough, the mouse starts to eat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry's smile fades.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He and Bill trade a look.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: I was just kidding ab--
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy lets rip a BELLOWING WAR CRY ("Yaaaahhh!")
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: and launches his baton like a spear, scaring the crap out of everyone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse ducks (yes, actually ducks) and the baton sail over his head close enough to ruffle its fur, bouncing off the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Apparently remembering a pressing engagement elsewhere, the mouse takes off in a flash toward the restraint room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy roars with frustration and takes off after it, trying to squash it with his heavy work shoes, leaping and stomping with great big galloping strides, missing the mouse by inches...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and thus is the Green Mile traversed, with Percy stomping and hollering like a spastic flamenco dancer, the convicts yelling at their bars, the mouse zigging and zagging like Jim Thorpe heading for the endzone...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse wins, zipping to safety under the restraint room door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy pounds his fist against the door in frustration:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: FUCK!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He fumbles with his keys, unlocks the door, yelling all the while:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: I'M GONNA RIP YOUR DISEASED HEAD OFF, YOU LITTLE PIECE OF SHIT!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OUTSIDE E BLOCK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Brutal are arriving for work--they pause, hearing PERCY'S YELLS drifting from the windows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The regular CONS in the yard are drifting curiously to the fence, wondering if a riot's brewing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Brutal take off running--
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSIDE E BLOCK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: --and rush in to find:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HARRY
{DIALOGUE}: Percy met your mouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Harry points.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Percy's down at the far end, rummaging wildly in the restraint room, tossing shit out onto the Mile.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PERCY
{DIALOGUE}: It's in here somewhere!
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna squish the little son of a bitch!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He starts muscling the filing cabinet out the door, kicking buckets out of his way.
