{DIALOGUE}: Angels.
{DIALOGUE}: Just like up in heaven...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FOUR PAIRS OF FEET come marching up the Green Mile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE ON COFFEY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul appears at the bars with Brutal, Harry, and Dean.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nothing is said.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey knows why they're here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rises as Brutal unlocks the cell, slides the door open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey steps out, looks around at their dazed and sad faces.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I be all right, fellas.
{DIALOGUE}: This here's the hard part.
{DIALOGUE}: I be all right in a little while.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul indicates St. Christopher medal around John's neck:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: John, I should have that just for now.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll give it back after.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John lets him take the necklace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul pockets it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They start to walk the Mile as:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: You know, I fell asleep this afternoon and had me a dream.
{DIALOGUE}: I dreamed about Del's mouse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Did you, John?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I dreamed he got down to that place Boss Howell talked about, that Mouseville place.
{DIALOGUE}: I dreamed there was kids, and how they laughed at his tricks!
{DIALOGUE}: My!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He laughs at the memory of it, then grows more serious:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I dreamed those two little blonde- headed girls were there.
{DIALOGUE}: They 'us laughing, too.
{DIALOGUE}: I put my arms around 'em and sat 'em on my knees, and there 'us no blood comin' outta their hair and they 'us fine.
{DIALOGUE}: We all watch Mr. Jingles roll that spool, and how we did laugh.
{DIALOGUE}: Fit to bus', we was.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind them, Dean stifles a sob.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL'S INNER OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey kneels.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul joins him, self-conscious and uncertain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: What should we pray for, John?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Strength?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul nods--strength it is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dean surprises Brutal and Harry by also kneeling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal and Harry hesitate...then join them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: God, please help us finish what we've started, and please welcome this man, John Coffey--like the drink, but not spelled the same-- into heaven and give him peace.
{DIALOGUE}: Please help us to see him off the best we can and let nothing go wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: Amen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul starts to rise, but Coffey takes his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I know a prayer I once heard.
{DIALOGUE}: Can I say it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You go right ahead, John.
{DIALOGUE}: Take all the time you need.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey closes his eyes, frowning in deep concentration.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Baby Jesus, meek and mild, pray for me...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Paul sees:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Kathe and Cora Detterick kneeling together in the enclosed porch that night, just before their bedtime:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: KATHE AND CORA
{DIALOGUE}: ...and every child.
{DIALOGUE}: Be my strength, be my friend...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then the vision is gone as:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: ...be with me until the end.
{DIALOGUE}: Amen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey rises, offers Paul his hand, helps him up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: EXECUTION CHAMBER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Full house tonight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bill Dodge is waiting at Old Sparky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence as Coffey is led in, all eyes on him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Klaus and Marjorie Detterick are in the front row.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She mutters:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: Die slow, you bastard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COFFEY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is faltering as Paul and Brutal bring him to the chair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: They's a lot of folks here hate me.
{DIALOGUE}: A lot.
{DIALOGUE}: I can feel it.
{DIALOGUE}: Like bees stinging me.
{DIALOGUE}: It hurts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{DIALOGUE}: Feel how we feel, then.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't hate you--can you feel that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey tries to take comfort in it, but flinches as:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: Kill him twice, you boys!
{DIALOGUE}: You go on and kill that raping baby- killer twice, that'd be fine!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She dissolves into tears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Klaus pulls her against his shoulder, looking dazed by the whole thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul and Brutal turn John around, sit him down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul notices Dean crying again, his back to the witnesses.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They kneel to apply the leg clamps, while Brutal and Harry secure the arms.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Wipe you face before you stand up, Dean.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dean nods, wiping his face with the sleeve of his coat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They rise, stepping back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This time, Paul's out front:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Roll on one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Van Hay cranks the generator.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lights flare hotter and brighter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's just like in Melinda's bedroom the night Coffey cured her with a kiss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Airless and bright, dreamlike.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: Does it hurt yet?
{DIALOGUE}: I hope it does!
{DIALOGUE}: I hope it hurts like hell!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: John Coffey...you have been condemned to die in the electric chair by a jury of your peers...sentence imposed by a judge in good standing in this state.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have anything to say before sentence is carried out?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John hesitates, nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry for what I am.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARJORIE
{DIALOGUE}: You ought to be!
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, you monster, you damn well ought to be!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal takes the mask from the hook to draw it over Coffey's head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey looks to Paul with terrified, pleading eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: Please, boss, don't put that thing over my face.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't put me in the dark, I's afraid of the dark.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: All right, John.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brutal puts the mask back, proceeds with the sponge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN TIGHT ANGLES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cap is lowered, the straps drawn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey is breathing fast, terrified, muttering under his breath:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{DIALOGUE}: ...heaven...I'm in heaven... heaven...heaven...heaven...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE WITNESSES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: sit and wait, barely breathing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JACK VAN HAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is poised at the switch, wondering why the order won't come.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAUL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: is staring at Coffey, unable to say the words.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRUTAL
{META_DATA}: (whispers)
{DIALOGUE}: Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: You have to say it.
{DIALOGUE}: You have to give the order.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul can't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches out and touches Coffey's hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their fingers clasp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In that moment, staring into his eyes, Paul hears the last thought that ever goes through Coffey's head:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COFFEY
{META_DATA}: (whispered V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He kill 'em with they love.
{DIALOGUE}: That's how it is ever' day.
{DIALOGUE}: All over the worl'...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their fingers disengage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul steps back, eyes still locked with Coffey's, and says the hardest words he's ever spoken:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Roll on two.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Van Hay throws the switch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey surges forward, fingers splayed and jittering past Old Sparky's arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lights begin blowing out all over the Mile, raining shattered glass and sparks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some of the witnesses scream.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A thin line of blood comes trickling out of Klaus Detterick's nose.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches up, absently wipes it away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey's eyes are locked on Paul's, riding the lightning all the way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finally slumps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Van Hay kills the current.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coffey's expression is peaceful, as if sleeping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A final pair of tears drift gently down his cheeks.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ACCESS TUNNEL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul ever so carefully replaces the St. Christopher's medal around Coffey's neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wheel him down the tunnel.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PAUL'S MODEL T - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul drives home, his heart numb.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PAUL'S HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul pulls in, cuts the engine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits for a moment, then gets out and heads for the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan steps out in her nightgown and robe to meet him on the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes him in her arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul can't hold it back anymore.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He breaks down sobbing against her as we
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NURSING HOME SUNROOM - PRESENT DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's late in the day as:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: That was the last execution I ever took part in.
{DIALOGUE}: Just couldn't do it anymore after that.
{DIALOGUE}: Brutal either.
{DIALOGUE}: We both transferred out, took jobs with Boys' Correctional.
{META_DATA}: (beat, nods)
{DIALOGUE}: That was all right.
{DIALOGUE}: Catch 'em young, that became my motto.
{DIALOGUE}: Might even have done some good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE SHIFTS TO Elaine listening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncertain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You don't believe me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't imagine you would lie to me, Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: It's just that...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: ...It's quite a story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Quite a story.
{META_DATA}: (pause)
{DIALOGUE}: One thing I don't understand.
{DIALOGUE}: You said you and Jan had a grownup son in 1935.
{DIALOGUE}: Is that right?
{META_DATA}: (Paul nods)
{DIALOGUE}: But if that's true...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: The math doesn't work, does it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She shakes her head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul thinks for a moment, comes to a decision.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You feel up to a walk?
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GEORGIA PINES - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rain has mostly stopped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad Dolan, back in street clothes, gets in his pickup truck and drives away...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NURSING HOME - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...while Paul and Elaine watch from a window.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GEORGIA PINES - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This time, we see two red specks trudging slowly up the ridge toward the treeline.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WOODS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul brings Elaine along the wooded path into view of the storage shacks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're both wearing ponchos.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: There.
{DIALOGUE}: It's in there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: This thing you want to show me.
{DIALOGUE}: Is it scary?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Scary?
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: Not really.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives her a smile, offers his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Paul approach through the grimy window as before, this time bringing Elaine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE SHIFTS to the door as they arrive, creaking open on rusty hinges to reveal them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They enter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine looks around at the musty nooks and crannies, wondering what they're doing here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul touchers arm, directs her attention:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: There.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine moves closer, sees it on the dusty floorboards:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old cigar box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a moment, she doesn't know what to make of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{DIALOGUE}: Wake up, old boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Wake up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine's breath catches in her throat...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...as a pair of bright oilspot eyes peer over the edge of the cigar box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a mouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His fur, once brown, is now all gray.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Paul?
{DIALOGUE}: It isn't...it can't be...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul gets down on the floor, holds out his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Come over here, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Come on over her and see this lady.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse tries several times to get over the side of the cigar box before he finally makes it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes to them, hobbling and crippled with arthritis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul pulls a slice of toast from his pocket, breaks off a small piece for the mouse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: That can't be Mr. Jingles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul says nothing, just pulls a spool from his pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Jingles might be old, but he's as obsessed as ever.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gets ready to fetch, eyes riveted to the spool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Softly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Messieurs et mesdames.
{DIALOGUE}: Beinvenue au cirque du mousie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul tosses the spool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse limps painfully after it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches it, goes around...and has to lay down to catch his breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine starts forward, but Paul holds her back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a moment, Mr. Jingles finds his feet again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rises and starts nosing the spool back to Paul.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Paul.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't make him do it again.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't bear to watch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{META_DATA}: (softly)
{DIALOGUE}: But he loves it so much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He glances around at the shack with a sad smile.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: This isn't exactly the Mouseville we had in mind...but we make do, don't we, old fella?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: As I live and breathe!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They gasp and spin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad Dolan stands in the doorway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Fooled you, didn't I Got yourself a little love nest here, I see...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pauses, seeing Mr. Jingles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: ...what the fuck?
{DIALOGUE}: Is that a mouse?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Don't hurt him, okay?
{DIALOGUE}: Okay?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: It's a goddamn mouse, y'old fool, they carry all kind'a disease...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad grabs an old garden hoe--the blade's rusted, but still sharp enough to cut a mouse in two.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: ...now step aside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul rushes in front of Brad, fists clenched, yelling:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You leave him alone, Percy!
{DIALOGUE}: You leave him alone, or by God I'll--
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad gives Paul a hard shove, pins him against the wall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Who you calling Percy?
{DIALOGUE}: Name's Brad, you senile fucker.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'm gonna nail that mouse, you can take that to the everfucking bank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine is suddenly at Brad's elbow, seething with fury:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: How dare you?
{DIALOGUE}: Get out!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Piss off, you wrinkeldy old bitch.
{DIALOGUE}: Me and Paulie are talking.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: His name is Mr. Edgecomb.
{DIALOGUE}: If you ever call him Paulie again, your days of employment at Georgia Pines will end.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Who the hell you think you are?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I am the grandmother of the man who is currently Speaker of the Georgia House of Representatives.
{DIALOGUE}: A man who loves his relatives, Mr. Dolan.
{DIALOGUE}: All it would take is a phone call.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad's smile falters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine steps closer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: At first I thought I'd let you be.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm old, and that seemed easiest.
{DIALOGUE}: But when my friends are threatened and abused, I do not let it be.
{META_DATA}: (icy beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Now get out, or you won't work another day here.
{DIALOGUE}: Not another hour.
{DIALOGUE}: I swear it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad eases his grip on Paul...and backs off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Don't know what you're getting so het up about.
{DIALOGUE}: Just a damn mouse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Get out, you ignorant man.
{DIALOGUE}: What little mind you have is ugly and misdirected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brad flushes red, heads for the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pauses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BRAD
{DIALOGUE}: Don't bother coming back here tomorrow...Mr. Edgecomb Gonna be a new lock on this door.
{DIALOGUE}: This is off-limits to residents, no matter what Mrs. My Shit Don't Stink has to say about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And off he goes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul tries to control the shaking in his hands, looks to Elaine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Little trick I learned from Percy Wetmore.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Is your grandson really Speaker of the House?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: He is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul bends down, picks Mr. Jingles up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: You gonna thank the lady?
{DIALOGUE}: She just saved your old mousie hide.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The mouse stretches his neck forward, nose twitching, smelling Paul's breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul looks to Elaine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Softly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I think Mr. Jingles happened by accident.
{DIALOGUE}: I think when we electrocuted Del, and it all went so badly...well, John could feel it, you know...and I think a tiny part of whatever was inside of him just leapt out...
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Me, I was no accident.
{DIALOGUE}: John had to give me a little part of himself...a gift, like...so I could see for myself what Wild Bill had done.
{DIALOGUE}: When John did that, a part of whatever power worked through him spilled into me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: He...what?
{DIALOGUE}: Infected you with life?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul looks at the mouse, strokes him gently between the ears.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: That's as good a word as any.
{DIALOGUE}: He infected us both, didn't he, Mr. Jingles.
{DIALOGUE}: With life.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a hundred and five years old, Elaine.
{DIALOGUE}: I was forty the year John Coffey walked the Green Mile.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: ...oh my God...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PUSHES SLOWLY IN on Paul as:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't even had a cold since 1935.
{DIALOGUE}: I've had to watch my friends and loved ones die off through the years...Hal and Melinda...Brutus Howell...my wife...my son...
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: ...and you, Elaine.
{DIALOGUE}: You'd die, too, and my curse is knowing I'll be there to see it...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FUNERAL HOME - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul, dressed in a dark suit, comes up the aisle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE SHIFTS to reveal Elaine Connelly lying in the open casket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...that's my punishment, you see?
{DIALOGUE}: My punishment for letting John Coffey ride the lightning...for killing a miracle of God...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul lays a rose atop the casket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...you'll be gone, like all the others, and I'll have to stay...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CEMETERY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul stands at the graveside as the casket is lowered.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll die eventually, I imagine.
{DIALOGUE}: I have no illusions of immortality.
{DIALOGUE}: But I will have wished for death long before death finds me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and walks away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In truth, I wish for it already.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. E BLOCK - NIGHT(1935)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Empty and silent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Paul walks the Mile alone, listening to the quiet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pauses, seeing something.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A whisper:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Jingles?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is Mr. Jingles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The little mouse is peering from under the restraint room door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's come home, looking bedraggled.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul bends down, gently picks him up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL
{DIALOGUE}: Where you been, boy?
{DIALOGUE}: I've been worried about you.
{DIALOGUE}: You hungry?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul turns and head back up the Green Mile, carrying the mouse cupped in his hands as we
{META_DATA}: MATCH DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NURSING HOME - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Young Paul transforms into Old Paul in the dissolve, the corridor of the Green Mile becoming the corridor of the nursing home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's walking along, holding the little mouse the same way he did over sixty years ago.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I lie in bed most nights, thinking about it.
{DIALOGUE}: And I wait...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PAUL'S BEDROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paul lies awake, staring at the moon outside his window.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I think about all the people I've loved, now long gone.
{DIALOGUE}: I think about my beautiful Jan, and how I lost her so many years ago.
{DIALOGUE}: I think about all of us walking our own Green Mile, each in our own time.
{DIALOGUE}: But one thought, more than any other, keeps me awake most nights...
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: ...if he could make a mouse live so long, how much longer do I have?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks over at the nightstand...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PAUL (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: We each owe a death, there are no exceptions, but sometimes, oh God, the Green Mile is so long...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ...and WE PAN to reveal Mr. Jingles sleeping fitfully in his cigar box, chasing that spool in his dreams as we
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT:
